ions of Renaissance artists about their viewers, shining a light on the process of discovery by some of the most inventive and intellectual artists of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Italian. 0aArt, RenaissancezItaly. 0aAudiencesxPsychology. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aAdolf von Hildebrand.  aAlbrecht Dürer.  aAltarpiece.  aAndrea Fulvio.  aAndrea Mantegna.  aAndrea Solari.  aAndrea del Sarto.  aAntonello da Messina.  aAntonio Rossellino.  aAretino.  aBacchus and Ariadne.  aBaptistery.  aBaroque architecture.  aBasilica.  aBembo.  aCamera degli Sposi.  aCaravaggio.  aCatullus.  aCecilia Gallerani.  aChiaroscuro.  aChrist among the Doctors (Dürer).  aConceit.  aCosimo de' Medici.  aCounter-Reformation.  aCristofano Allori.  aDella Rovere.  aDiego Velázquez.  aDonatello.  aDuke of Florence.  aEdward Burne-Jones.  aEpigram.  aFamulus.  aFeast of the Gods (art).  aFilarete.  aFilippino Lippi.  aGalleria Borghese.  aGinevra de' Benci.  aGiorgio Vasari.  aGiorgione.  aGiovanni Bellini.  aGiovanni Pisano.  aGiulio Romano.  aGrand manner.  aHercules and Cacus.  aHeroides.  aHigh Renaissance.  aHigh place.  aHyperbole.  aIntentionality.  aJan van Eyck.  aLas Meninas.  aLateran Baptistery.  aLodovico Dolce.  aMadonna of the Harpies.  aMario Equicola.  aMario Praz.  aMarriage of the Virgin (Perugino).  aMasaccio.  aMaster of the Virgo inter Virgines.  aMichelangelo.  aMona Lisa Smile.  aMystery play.  aNational Gallery of Art.  aOrlando Furioso.  aParagone.  aParmigianino.  aPersius.  aPesaro Madonna.  aPetrarch.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertThe A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Packagez978311129290840uhttps://doi.org/10.15